<styl>by <m0>By MICHELE CHANDLER<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>  In an effort to restore profitability, financially troubled Physician Corp. of America said Monday that it has sold its 40 medical clinics in Florida and its underperforming HMOs in Georgia and Alabama.<ep>
   And Miami-based PCA said its losses narrowed in the first quarter, while revenues and HMO enrollment climbed.<ep>
   The state's largest provider of health services to poor and disabled people receiving Medicaid, PCA has suffered since last year from higher-than-expected medical expenses and significant cutbacks in Medicaid reimbursement rates.<ep>
   Looking for a remedy, PCA signed up investment bank Bear Stearns & Co. last fall to explore financial options and assist with the sale of its out-of-state HMOs.<ep>
   On Monday, PCA's shares closed unchanged at $14.87 1/2, near its 52-week low of $13.50.<ep>
   The company called its quarterly loss of $4.9 million ``a significant improvement'' over the fourth quarter of 1995, when PCA lost $36.5 million. In the first quarter, PCA's Florida HMOs reported losses of $16.1 million, versus a $22.9 million loss in the fourth quarter of last year.<ep>
   The results mean PCA's efforts during the past several months to boost profitability are begining to show results, PCA executives said.<ep>
   ``The Florida turnaround is progressing and is expected to be completed in 1996,'' said Stanley Kardatzke, PCA's chairman and chief executive.<ep>
   While first-quarter losses exceeded his projections, ``The bad news out of the earnings isn't the whole story,'' said Robert Mains, health care analyst with First Albany. ``There are some other things going on behind the scenes that I think are positive.''<ep>
   Among them:<ep>
   (box) PCA sold its 125-physician network and 40 affiliated clinics for $23 million to FPA Medical Management, a physician practice management company based in San Francisco. The clinics, which treated only PCA patients, <m1><styl>cxon<ql>
